Predicting Liked Songs

Riley Zamora

2023-03-16

Introduction

The goal of this project is to create a classification model that uses song data from Spotify and can predict whether a person likes a song or not.

Spotify

Spotify is an audio streaming and media services platform. The company has over 100 million songs available on their platform, and even better they have specific data on each-and-every song. My model will be able to look at any song’s data and predict whether it is liked.

What Determines whether a Song is liked?

In this project, the dataset titled ‘Spotify Recommendation’, posted on Kaggle by Brice Vergnou, consists of 195 songs from Spotify, with 100 labeled as liked songs and 95 as disliked songs. However, my original idea was to compile and create a data set myself using Spotify’s data to be to predict what music I like. When all is said and done, I may still pursue this idea.

Why?

Music has been around arguably as long as people have. There is always new music being released and if I could predict which of these new songs I like I would always have an updated playlist and never get sick of listening to the same music all the time.

Check Correlation

spotify %>%

  cor() %>%

Looking at this corrplot(), we can see which variables are positively and negatively correlated:

  • Danceability is most highly correlated with valence, and has some correlation with loudness and speechiness.
  • Energy is highly correlated with loudness. This is a pretty obvious correlation in my opinion, the louder the music the more energy it has. Rock music is going to be loud and have high energy.
  • Intrumentalness and danceability are very negatively correlated. I am not sure if I am shocked by this or not. On one hand I can see how a slow guitar song would not make me want to dance, but at the same time piano is considered acoustic and there have been some wild piano players that could make you wanna shake your booty.
  • Again acousticness and energy have a low correlation. I could believe that the data we have may consider acousticness as strictly slow piano or guitar music.

These are the main correlations in the data set and we can take a further look into them.

Data Splitting and Cross Validation

We split the data stratifying on the variable liked to ensure that the proportion of observations with each level of our outcome variable is the same. This is a random process so we set a seed in the computer to make sure we can reproduce our results. We are using the library tidymodels() which allows us to make an initial split of the data. We can then take the split data and assign a specified proportion (80%) of it to a training set and the rest of the data to a testing set. The training set will be used to train our models on the data the we have. Once we have chosen our best fit model we can test its accuracy on the testing set.

Remove Mode

I decided to remove the variable mode because it had a value of 1 or 0 for major or minor. It seems to not be the best predictor so I removed it.

spotify <- spotify %>% 
  subset(select = -mode)

Split the Data

set.seed(42) # The meaning of life (Hitchhikers Guide)

spotify_split <- initial_split(spotify, prop = 0.80,
                                strata = liked)
spotify_train <- training(spotify_split)
spotify_test <- testing(spotify_split)

We have a pretty small data set so this makes sense. Spotify as an entire platform does this with every song that an individual has listened to. This is the purpose of being able to like a song on Spotify. However, if you are like me and only add songs to playlists, they keep track of how often you listen to a track.

K-fold Cross-Validation

Resampling techniques such as k-fold cross-validation allow us to test our model to its fullest ability. If we chose not to resample we could face over fitting our model. K-fold cross-validation involves dividing the data into k subsets, using k-1 of them to train the model. The final subset is then used to evaluate the model performance. This process is repeated k times with each subset serving as the test set exactly one time. This reduces the risk of over-fitting/under-fitting.

We need 3 things to use k-fold cross-validation:

  1. a workflow w/ one or more arguments marked for tuning.
  2. a vfold_cv: resample object of the cross-validation; essentially set number of folds.
  3. a tune grid: set of predefined values for each of the hyperparameters.
set.seed(42)
spotify_folds <- vfold_cv(spotify_train, v=5, strata='liked')

Since our data set is relatively small, I chose to use 5 folds in our cross-validation to ensure no over-fitting occurs. I also chose to stratified sampling on liked so that each fold has a representative sample of the outcome variable.

Model Fitting

To begin model fitting, I made a recipe that contained all the predictor variables. We have some categorical values that are pre-dummycoded in the dataset. I am not sure how the recipe will treat these values so I ran step_dummy() anyways. I also normalized all my predictor variables.

How do we analyze our models?

For a classification model, we want to look at the roc_auc or accuracy to determine model performance. The roc_auc measures the area under the ROC (Receiver Operating Characteristic) curve, which plots the true positive rate against the false positive rate for different threshold values. ROC AUC can be a useful metric when the classes in your problem are imbalanced or when you care more about correctly identifying one class over the other. We can also check our model accuracy which is simply a measure of how many correct predictions were made when compared to the true data.

We are mostly going to be looking at the accuracy measurement to analyze these models because our data set is relatively small and balanced.

Create a Recipe

The perk of using tidymodels() is that we can create one recipe and use it for all of our models.

spotify_recipe <- recipe(liked ~ ., data=spotify_train) %>%
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors()) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_predictors())

Logistic Regression

First, we set up our logistic regression model using logistic_reg(). We set the engine to glm and the mode to classification. We need to make sure to specify that it is a classification model and not a regression model.

# Set model 
log_mod <- logistic_reg() %>% 
  set_engine('glm') %>% 
  set_mode('classification')

Then, we can set up workflow and add the logistic regression model:

# Create workflow
log_wkflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(log_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(spotify_recipe)

Finally, we can fit the model to our folded data:

#log_fit <- fit_resamples(log_wkflow, spotify_folds)

Random Forest

First, we set up our random forest model tuning on mtry, trees, and min_n. We set mode as classification because we are predicting a categorical value.

rf_mod <- rand_forest(mtry = tune(),trees = tune(),min_n = tune()) %>% 
  set_engine('ranger',importance = "impurity") %>% 
  set_mode('classification')

Then, we set up my workflow using the mode we just created above as well as our recipe:

rf_wkflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_recipe(spotify_recipe) %>%
  add_model(rf_mod)

Now, we set up a regular grid so that each hyper parameter has a preset value to run off. I chose mtry to range from 1 to 12 because that is how many parameters we have in the model. I chose a range of 100 to 500 trees because I do not have a very large data set and I still wanted to be able to have a concise model. I chose min_n to be anywhere from 5 to 50 because our model is not that big.

rf_grid <- grid_regular(mtry(range=c(1,12)),
                        trees(range=c(100,500)),
                        min_n(range=c(5,50)),
                        levels = 8)

knn_wkflow <- workflow() %>%

While this model does not perform as well as the random forest or logistic regression models, it’s worth noting that the best accuracy model has 1 to 5 neighbors, and the best roc_auc model has 15 neighbors. If I had to choose between these two models, I would prefer the one with 15 neighbors since roc_auc takes into account the trade-offs between precision and recall, whereas accuracy only considers the number of correct predictions. This decision is based on the table provided. Additionally, considering the graph posted above, we can see that the model with 13 neighbors has the second highest roc_auc and the fifth highest accuracy. If I were to choose k-Nearest Neighbors as my model, I would probably choose 13 neighbors to continue my predictions.

Variable Importance

Lets see what variables were the most important in predicting whether a song was liked or disliked.

Note that we specify importance = “impurity” in the workflow setup above; this is so that we can use extract_fit_parsnip() and vip() to create and view a variable importance plot

rf_final_fit %>% extract_fit_parsnip() %>% 
  vip() + 
  theme_minimal()

Instrumentalness was the most important predictor in determining whether a track was liked or disliked by Vergnou. Liveliness was the least important at predicting the outcome of a track. I would conclude that this is because liveliness is pretty well distributed between both liked and disliked songs.

It is important to recall that this data is based off of the music taste of Vergnou as he is the one created it. Like I said early on I would love to create my own data set and be able to predict whether I would like a song solely based off of its attributes provided by Spotify.

Lets take a look at the roc_auc score for the prediction of a disliked song; .pred_0.

roc_curve(augment(rf_final_fit_auc, new_data = spotify_test), truth = liked, .pred_0) %>% 
  autoplot()

You can see that our model is not perfect, but to train a perfect model takes a lot more computational time and an extremely well fit model. Machine learning models are trained to make predictions based on patterns in the data used for training. However, it is often difficult to create a model that perfectly fits the data, as this can result in overfitting. To avoid overfitting, machine learning models are often trained with a certain amount of regularization, which balances the trade-off between model complexity and accuracy. This regularization helps to prevent the model from becoming too complex and overfitting the data, but may result in a less-than-perfect fit.

Conclusion

To wrap up this model building project, I will first discuss our goals, models and outcome. Then, I will talk about any future projects and how I would continue to work on this model. Lastly, I will go over my final thoughts from the project and the class overall.

Discussion

The purpose of this project was to build a machine learning model that, given data on selected songs, could predict whether a song was liked or disliked. We used a dataset titled ‘Spotify Recommendation’ posted on Kaggle.com by Brice Vergnou, which contained 195 observations of 13 predictor variables and 1 outcome variable. The data was compiled by Vergnou and included 95 disliked songs and 100 liked songs.

We conducted some dataset analysis and found that the predictor mode was probably not the best, so we removed it and continued by splitting the data into a training set and a testing set. The training set was used to build a recipe for a total of 4 models: Logistic Regression, Random Forest, K-Nearest Neighbors, and Decision Tree.

After fitting the models, we found that the Logistic Regression and the Random Forest models had the highest accuracy, respectively. We then fit these models to our test set and were able to conclude that the Random Forest model was the best model to predict whether a song was liked or disliked. We noted that even though a model may have the highest accuracy when testing with training set data, it does not necessarily perform as well on the test set. This is why we used k-fold cross-validation. We also noted that the logistic regression model trained on the folded data was more representative of how our model would actually perform.

Our Decision Tree and K-Nearest Neighbor models, were not the best fit for our data. This is not to say that these types of model are never a useful option, it just means that the Spotify data was not good for these models. This highlights the importance testing multiple models on a data set and not being a lazy statistician.

Our Random Forest model was able to predict whether a song was liked or disliked with 89% accuracy, which I am pretty happy with for my first major machine learning project. We found that the intrumentalness and liveliness were the best and worst predictors of the outcome, respectively. We can visualize our data to know exactly why this was, but in all honesty, it depends on an individuals music taste.
